the following is the most appropriate initial action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Report the colleague immediately to the medical board","Discuss concerns privately with the colleague and offer support","Directly confront the colleague about their behaviour","Share concerns with other staff members informally","Ignore the behaviour as it may be temporary"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscuss concerns privately with the colleague and offer support\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach shows professional respect while addressing the concerning behaviour, and may help identify underlying issues that require assistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are inappropriate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly confront the colleague about their behaviour\u003C/strong\u003E - A confrontational approach may be counterproductive and damage professional relationships\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReport the colleague immediately to the medical board\u003C/strong\u003E - This is premature without first attempting to understand and address the situation directly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgnore the behaviour as it may be temporary\u003C/strong\u003E - This risks patient safety and fails to support a colleague who may need help\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShare concerns with other staff members informally\u003C/strong\u003E - This could constitute unprofessional gossip and breach colleague confidentiality\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the initial supportive discussion does not lead to improvement, or if patient safety is at immediate risk, escalation to supervisors or other appropriate authorities may then be necessary. The focus should be on supporting the colleague while ensuring patient safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn reference to mandatory notifications to AHPRA, a non-treating health practitioner is required to make a mandatory notification if they have formed a \u0027reasonable belief\u0027 that someone is either impaired, intoxicated while practising, demonstrating a significant departure from accepted professional standards, or there is sexual misconduct. A \u0027reasonable belief\u0027 requires direct knowledge of misconduct, not just suspicion or speculation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early recognition of concerning changes in colleague behaviour is important for patient safety and colleague wellbeing.","Signs of impairment include changes in behaviour, performance, and professional interactions.","Healthcare workers have a professional duty to act on concerns about colleague impairment."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx","https://www.ahpra.gov.au/Notifications/mandatorynotifications/Mandatory-notifications.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86435"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18897"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86435"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T13:04:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T13:04:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11630"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104115"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"creat